English ''adjective''

p&uacute;n&bull;gent  &mdash;  (p&uuml;n&prime;j&euml;nt)

===Pronunciation===

*{{audio|en-us-pungent.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Definition===

:;1. Affecting the organs of taste or smell with a strong, bold, or sharp sensation.
:: '''''a.''''' penetrating in taste or smell, 
:::usually used to mean a stong bothersome, overwhelming, <br>unpleasant, disgusting, or gross taste or smell.
:: '''''b.''''' overpowering [[odor]]/[[odour]] that stings the nose, 
:::said especially of [[acidic]], [[spicy]], and [[bitter]] substances.
:::* "tasting the ''pungent'' wood sap"
:::* "The lasagna included plenty of ''pungent'' garlic."
:::* "a ''pungent'' smell of burning sulfur"
:::* "the ''pungent'' smell of amonia"
:;2. capable of wounding
:: '''''a.''''' Penetrating, biting, or caustic
:: '''''b.''''' To the point; sharp, barbed
:: '''''c.''''' Possibly polite, but short and with high tension
:::* "There were ''pungent'' talks during which, the major issues were confronted."
:::* "a ''pungent'' compliment"
:::* "a ''pungent'' [[aphorism]]"
:::* "''pungent'' satire"
:;3. Pointed
:::* "a ''pungent'' leaf."

===Other Uses===

'''pungent''' ({{compar}} '''more pungent''', {{superl}} '''most pungent''')

''noun'' – pun’gen&bull;cy
''adverb'' – pun’gent&bull;ly

===Background===

[Latin <tt>pung&euml;ns</tt>, <tt>pungent-</tt>, the present participle of <tt>pungere</tt>, "''to sting''"; 
see <tt>peuk-</tt> in Indo-European roots.]

